The Fair Sentencing Act, Then and Now

Section two of the Fair Sentencing Act (FSA) of 2010 lowers the sentencing disparity between crack cocaine from 100 to 1 down to 18 to 1 in favor of powdered cocaine. The Anti-Drug Abuse Act or the ADAA of 1986 was the law which stood for 24 years that created the discriminatory ratio of 100 to 1 (FSA 2010). The history of of the FSA dates back to the official declaration of a “War on Drugs” by then president Ronald Reagan in the 1980’s, piled with mass hysteria and mass media coverage crack cocaine negatively affecting the inner city communities. As a result of the concerns of the American public as a result of exaggerated media coverage of bad crack was, the extremely punitive and discriminate Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986 was created. The ADAA resulted in increased population for everyone especially African Americans of low socioeconomic status, destroying communities because of the lopsided ratios that targeted crack cocaine (not powder cocaine) users and sellers. Overtime, the narrative of the dangerousness of crack cocaine has ceased to an extent, which allowed room for FSA to be passed in 2010. While the FSA closed the gap to 100:1 from 18:1, there were still  preconceived notions of crack cocaine that affected people’s mindset of the drug; despite powder and crack cocaine being two separate forms of the same drug. Many believe that there will be an equal playing field in sentencing when ratio becomes 1:1 in favor of neither crack or powder cocaine.

The Fair Sentencing Act of 2010 (specifically Section 2) changes the former Anti Drug Abuse Law of 1986 by lowering the five year mandatory minimum of the possession of crack cocaine from five to 28 grams of crack. The law also lowers the amount of crack cocaine that would constitute a ten year mandatory minimum from 50 grams to 280 grams of crack cocaine (Associates, 2009) . What the Fair Sentencing Act essentially does is it discriminates against low socioeconomic, minorities or susceptible to possessing and selling crack cocaine on a lesser level than the government did before at the inception of the War on Drugs. Many people against a crack vs powder cocaine disparity would argue, “We are going from destroying poor minority filled communities a lot, to destroying poor minority filled communities on a less regular basis”. But at the same time The Fair Sentencing Act closed the gap substantially which helped Americans (African Americans and Latinos) that were culturally and economically attached to crack rock not get completely rolled over by the law.

Prior to the FSA, there was the Anti Drug Abuse Act that was the precedent before the FSA made the crack vs powder cocaine discrepancy less lopsided. In the mid 1980’s, crack cocaine completely changed the culture of the United States of America. It viciously attacked the major inner cities of the U.S. within two to three years, American citizens and politicians were pushing for legislation that came from that could end or mitigate the terror that were crack cocaine and its distributors. From Actors like Ossie Davis and Governors such as Mario Cuomo condemning crack as pushing for stringent laws against crack, it almost became certain that bills suppressing crack use would become laws instantaneously (Mann, 2013). For example, African American politician Walter Fauntroy described crack cocaine as “The Plague” and said “Every area of our life, every institution of our society is being affected by this tragedy and high cost of drug abuse” (Mann, 2013). He believed that mainly crack was an entity that threatened the very essences of civil society. As stated in the aforementioned paragraph, the result of the crack epidemic was the commencement of extremely punitive laws, starting with the Anti Drug Law in 1986. But before Ronald Reagan declared a War on Drugs, another infamous U.S. president did the same; Richard Nixon. (Briefly) In 1971, then president Nixon declared a War on Drugs which created agencies like the DEA to enforce drug use/sale and made marijuana a schedule one drug which meant it was one of the most restrictive drugs (A Brief History of the Drug War). As time went on marijuana was becoming decriminalized. Soon after Reagan became president, he declared the new War on Drugs and inner cities of the U.S. felt the wrath of the Anti Drug Abuse Act of 1986 when he signed it into law.

As stated previously, after over 20 years of the pillaging of inner city minority neighborhoods, the notion that crack cocaine was destructive force terrorizing America has mostly died down. In came the FSA, which significantly (but not entirely) helped the communities and minorities that were ADAA by lowering the ratio from 100:1 to 18:1, but like most laws that have been put in place, it has never been that easy in terms of a seamless transition. Court decisions always come into play whenever there’s a controversial law. A court decision that had an impact on how the FSA was enforced/that affect how the law was going to work was the United States vs Gomes case. Back in 2010, Gregory Anthony Gomes pled guilty to several counts of distribution of crack. One of the charges was “conspiracy to possess with the intent to distribute fifty grams or more of cocaine base (crack)” which met the requirements of the mandatory minimum of five years. The Appellant (Gomes), made the argument that court made an error in giving him the mandatory minimum based on the new Fair Sentencing Act which would make him ineligible for the mandatory sentencing. The unfortunate occurrence was that the appellant committed the crimes in 2010, before the FSA became a law, which bars him from being able to evade mandatory sentencing. The initial text of the FSA states, “Accordingly, the previous statutory mandatory minimum threshold quantities, will continue to apply for all offense conduct that occurred prior to the date of enactment of the new law” (FSA 2010). Gomes committed /or arrested for the offense before the Fair Sentencing Act was ever signed into law, so he was adjudicated how someone in 1987 convicted of those same crimes would be adjudicated. This court case, as with other court cases involving the same issues have shown us how we are not that much removed from laws that are unfair and discriminatory to poor minorities (with the idea of white people caught up in crack offenses are a type of collateral damage in this instance). And although the results of United States vs Gomes were finalized after the FSA became law, the case showed why the FSA almost had to be implemented. What was gut wrenching was that; the law gave him absolutely leeway because he was arrested prior to the law changing, understandably so because of what the law states regarding that. Another case that was controversial in the sense that the FSA was being used to help exonerate a prisoner was United States vs Blewett. The Blewett case went to the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit in 2013 after the defendants were adjudicated on the ADAA in 2005 for a crack cocaine offense. Before appealing, the defendants were denied relief for re-sentencing in district court (Zoukis, 2013).The Sixth Circuit reversed the district court’s decision and granted Blewett relief which changed the culture of crack cocaine offenses located ONLY in the Sixth Circuit jurisdiction. But with that decision can start an influx of lighter sentences of crack charges under the FSA for prisoners adjudicated before the FSA became a law.

The Fair Sentencing Act has made a significant stride toward equality; eradicating the cruel and discriminatory ADAA that was created out of spite and emotion channeled in the wrong direction. Despite these somewhat impressive strides, the enforcement of the FSA is still biased. Based on how the federal law is constructed, it leaves a gap (despite lowering the ratio) for the enforcement of the law to continue bias. The ADAA (1986) created the 100:1 ratio that was biased against lower class minorities and the FSA amended the 1986 law which substantially lowered the ratio to 18:1 which took less weight off the scale. There is apparently still a big enough difference between crack and powder cocaine that groups of people are continuing to be subject to more severe punishments because they have a crack charge. Crack and powder cocaine are two forms of the same drug and have the almost the same negative effects on the body however they are consumed (Barcy, 2015). So even after the implementation of the FSA you still clearly see the criminalization of the Black and Brown community, the preconceived notions that one drug is worse than the other and so the image of a criminal is created. Therefore creating a biased environment where “criminals” need to be reprimanded which makes it easier for lower class peoples to be swept under the rug. The bias (not at the level it was 20 years ago), shows itself in the fact that 80 percent of the 30,000 plus federal inmates imprisoned because of crack cocaine are Black, a year after the FSA became federal law (Garcia, 2013). Bias against Blacks is still prevalent in prisons as a result of the FSA not completely ending the sentencing disparity. You will still see disproportionately larger sentences for the same drug on a federal level.

The overall effectiveness of the FSA can be viewed from two main perspectives. Whether it was effective because it reduced the sentencing disparity and lowering the occurrences of unequal treatment of minorities? Or Whether the FSA wasn’t at all effective because it didn’t end the discrepancy? I will look at it from the glass half full perspective because the FSA didn’t go backwards in its effort to gain equality. Although the ratio is still in favor of powder cocaine, sentencing decreased at a moderate amount from 2009 to 2014 in state and federal compared to the mid 1980’s to about the 1990’s where incarceration rates doubles as a result of the drug wars (Sentencing 2016). Furthermore, according to the U.S. Department of Justice, there has been a significant (88%) decrease  in correctional populations from 2007-2014, which is a candid reflect of the animus towards crack cocaine decreasing along with the implementation of the FSA (Kaeble, 2015). While we are moving in the right direction with the FSA, this type of discrimination won’t cease, but if incremental strides toward just are being made, the law is somewhat effective.

The procedures that are used to enforce the Fair Sentencing Act is the lowering of the sentencing disparity of crack cocaine from 100:1 to 18:1 ratio, attempting to close the gap of the discriminatory ADAA. I found that in California, Governor Brown signed the California FSA in 2014 which completely eliminated the disparity between powder cocaine and crack cocaine. It was modeled after the federal FSA but California took it a step further by equaling a once discriminatory playing field. As of 2015, there are only eleven remaining states that continue to have the drug disparity therefore have not legislated in the same direction of the FSA (2014). So what followed suit with most of the states was an understanding of fairness through the FSA was states like California and other states taking the initiative of acting on the former discriminatory law and using the FSA as a building block to end the disparity. Another interesting point was that in 2011, former Attorney General Eric Holder sent a memorandum to all federal prosecutors regarding the new law (Holder, 2011). He update prosecutors on what the FSA and explicitly tells them that the new penalties apply to only defendants sentenced on or after August 3rd 2010. Any time prior to that date in which a defendant is sentenced, prosecutors have to adjudicate them under the ADAA. So prosecutors should change their methods only if defendants were sentenced on the day or after the FSA became law.

While the FSA is a law that has gone in the right direction in terms of mitigating discrimination in prisons, it could use some fine tuning. An idea that I have for reforming the law to make the ratio 1:1 instead of 18:1, in favor of neither crack or powder cocaine. Since the two drugs are different forms of the same entity, they should be treated as such. Any other ratio creates a discriminatory environment that will continue to subjugate minorities. Some states still have a disparity in their own versions of the FSA, if the federal ratio is lowered to 1:1, states will be inclined to follow suit. So in terms of enforcement, the federal influence will affect public opinion and legislature (i.e. California FSA).

The FSA is a step in the right direction. We have definitely come a long way from the times where everyone should fear the “super predators” that were the results of the media outrage towards crack. But the present day serves as hope for the future with the FSA and states taking charge and ending sentencing ratios for crack, but a federal 18:1 in favor of powder cocaine shows us that our mission hasn’t fully been accomplished.


